	   <a name=103736576252725></a>
	   <form action=http://www1.allakhazam.com/perl/strategy/mrate.pl name=f103736576252725><tr><td id=headerrow><a id=sj href=classes.html?class=15&mid=103736576252725>RE: Chain Summoning</a> <a id=fs8 href=classes.html?class=15&mid=103736576252725#post><img src=http://everquest.allakhazam.com/static/reply.gif border=0 alt="Reply..." height=16 width=16></a></td><td align=right id=headerrow valign=bottom><span id=notbold>By:</span> <a href=poster.html?user=61546><span id=Sage>Slipskin</span></a>, <span id=Sage>Sage</span><br><span id=notbold>851 posts</td></tr>
	   <tr><td colspan=1 id=headerrow>Posted @ Fri, Nov 15th 8:30 AM 2002</td>
	   <td id=headerrow align=right><span id=notbold>Score</span>: Decent<span id=notbold>[3.43]</span></td></tr>
	   <tr><td colspan=2>Fairly new tactic for Beastlords. Basically, it goes like this:<br><br>When your warder's health bar is down to less than one bubble you start casting your Spirit of.... spell to summon a new pet.&nbsp;&nbsp;The new warder is at full health and level but it is unbuffed.  Your old warder is immediately destroyed; whether or not it ran out of HP.  Chain summoning can save your life but you will drain a lot of mana resummoning and rebuffing. The good news is that we don't need reagents like Magicians and other pet classes.  <br><br>Timing is critical. If you don't summon the new warder before the old one dies you will get the aggro.  If that happens you may not get the next summons off in time.<br>&nbsp;<br></td></tr>
	   <tr><td colspan=1 >&nbsp;</td><td align=right valign=bottom>
	   <span style='font-weight: normal; font-size: 9px;'>[<a href=#top>Top</a>]</span></tr>
